headline: Why the Israeli army doubts Hamas can be demilitarized
subhead: The second phase of Donald Trump's 'peace plan' for Gaza calls for the disarmament of the Islamist group. However, Israeli security leaders are convinced that it will continue to maneuver in order to maintain its capacity for both military and terrorist action.

subhead: The army-backed Union Solidarity and Development Party is poised for a sweeping victory in a vote critics say is tightly controlled by the junta and designed to entrench military rule nearly five years after the coup.

headline: Brave1, the online armory supplying Ukraine's troops, reveals the limits of its efficiency
subhead: The platform, which was created to boost defense sector innovation and offset Russia's material superiority, helped Ukrainian units quickly obtain supplies. However, it also risks reaching a cap of technological sophistication.

headline: Inside the workshop where dress forms are made
subhead: For 160 years, the French company Stockman has been handcrafting dress forms used by fashion designers, costume makers and aspiring stylists to refine their creations. This centuries-old expertise allows Stockman to meet custom requests from around the world.

headline: Venezuela and the US: A century of turbulent oil relations
subhead: At the heart of an energy partnership and later an ideological clash, oil turned Venezuela into a strategic ally for Washington, before turning it into a target of Donald Trump's ambitions.

headline: An era of distrust emerges between the US and its Western allies
subhead: Donald Trump's suggestion that the US could seize Greenland by force has exposed the strategic isolation his administration has chosen, in disregard for the country's commitments. Even though the Republican president abandoned the idea at Davos, the damage to US credibility is substantial.

headline: How surveillance companies track smartphone users through advertising data
subhead: Companies are offering law enforcement agencies the ability to track smartphone users through advertising data gathered on their devices. Le Monde attended confidential presentations of these new surveillance tools to learn more.
